results.notes:
A NJMA foray collection. The younger fruiting body found by me in pine-dominated woods with some oaks and other hardwoods mixing in. The second, postmature mushrooms was brought in to the ID table by an unknown foray participant and was recognized by me as the same species.
This pallid trich discolors yellow and then brown and this staining is its most salient feature. I don’t think I’ve ever seen this species before, and no attempt was made by anyone present at the foray to put a name on it. If anyone recognizes this species, please suggest an ID.
The smaller mushroom was preserved and will be sequenced.

results.notes: Two fruiting bodies were growing in live oak leaf duff, under the canopy and about 4 yards from the nearest trunk of a mature, multi-trunked live oak tree. Even closer (2-3 feet) was a mature manzanita tree, alive but mostly cut back by human pruning. Stone road came next, so this was at the edge of a live oak patch. One fruiting body (called “2nd” in photos) was older and cap was planar; one fruiting body (called “main” in photos) was just emerging. The latter had more of the classic orange-brown, orange-salmon color of proposed species. A third fruiting body in area was dry and past ID stage, but of similar stature and universal veil patch—likely a third of the same that had fruited even earlier. Soaking spring rain 3 days prior to collection day.

results.notes: Morphology: conical to broadly-conical cap reddish-brown (btw. Cinnamon and Dresden brown) with faint whitish streaks midway to outer translucently striate margin (fading to pale Chamois when dry with Walnut brown marginal edge); gills convex within cap border, adnexed to free, pale Wood brown fading to nearly whitish at edge; very lustrous bright white robust stem, staining Snuff brown or golden, whitish-buff pseudorhiza with network of short fine roots. Spore print: black. Measurements: [n=3] cap 7.00-13.8 mm across by 4.8-12.6 tall, stem 0.9-2.2 thick (nearly equal) by 44.5-64.8 tall (44.9-50.6% pseudorhiza). Growth pattern: gregarious. Habitat: loose rather moist loamy soil slightly admixed with woody debris at trailside emerging from amongst leaves.

results.notes:
This fruiting began on (or just prior to) 03/31/2024. The initially observed fruit bodies may be seen at obs 547617. Older observations are linked there.
Pits pruinose.
Spores 20-25(27) x 13-16.
Fruit bodies collected and studied from previous years (same exact location) were sequenced twice. At first there were several names representing Morchella section Distantes that appeared with high %Ident via GenBank BLAST. More data has accumulated since then, and now the BLAST matches of ITS are dominated by M. norvegiensis (many labeled as M. eohespera, a synonym of M. norvegiensis). See obs 407533 and obs 452106.

results.notes:
Large fruiting coating a fallen Alnus rubra.
Reddish brown overall with minute shelving above pores.
Harvested two sections.
Applied 3% KOH to surface. Darkened, but no distinct change after 5 minutes.
Removed thin pore layer surface/tissue and mounted in 3% KOH on a glass slide.
MICROSCOPY:

Setae: abundant along outer edge of tissue. Long and spear like with fine pointed/sharp tips.
Basidia: 4 sterigmate.
Hyphae: Septate, notched, notch points slightly flaring at intersection or where separated.
Spores: Ellipsoid, with a single guttule(oil dot) in center of each spore(appearing like black eyed peas). Very small, thin walled.
All macroscopic and microscopic features match for F. ferruginosa.
Dehydrating both specimens to bag for herbarium collection/genetic record.

results.notes: There were 3 specimens (one of which was in prime condition) near one live oak and 1 prime specimen with flatter top (apparently a bit older) near a second, adjacent live oak in a hilltop wooded area. First I’ve seen in years. Prime specimen was 10 cm high, cap 8 cm wide, stipe 2-3 cm wide. Was surprised when nominal 3% KOH solution did not turn cap yellow, but source reagent was some 9 years old, so ordered fresh, reagent grade KOH, made up fresh 4% KOH stock, retested on refrigerated specimen (2nd “prime” above), and got expected yellow reaction, a little better on stipe vs. cap, but definitely there on both. One section of stem on 1st sample had central area but not stuffed at one level, whereas at other heights, very solid white. Spores from 1st prime specimen examined microscopically and stained amyloid.

results.notes:
Single mature fruiting beneath Douglas fir.
Stem: pruinose, large abrupt bulb at base.
Cap: brownish orange, umbonate. Radial fibrils around darker central disc.
Odor: none detected.
Harvested specimen.
Removed single gill and mounted in 3% KOH on a glass slide.
Spore print: grayish brown.
Microscopy:
Spores: ellipsoid, medium sized, smooth, thick walled.
Cheilocystidia: Metuloid, large, thick walled with encrusted golden tips.
The occurrence in spring, completely pruinose stem with abrupt bulb, brownish orange cap with raised fibrillose disc, smooth ellipsoid spores and encrusted cheilocystidia match well for Inocybe praecox.
Dehydrating specimen for herbarium collection/genetic record.

Basidia: 4 sterigmate. Broadly clavate rounded in shape.

results.notes:
Fruiting on the cut end of a fallen Alnus rubra.
Harvested 12 specimens attached to portion of host/substrate.
Analyzed/photographed large setae at home with Apexel 12/24X macro lens attachment.
Performed crush mount of tissue in Lugol’s solution and 3% KOH.
MICROSCOPY:
Spores: multiguttulate(multiple small granular dots/granules within each spore). Elliptical, ovoid. Spores slightly wrinkled/verrucose. Medium/large in size.
Asci: 8 spored, cylindrical. Non-amyloid.
Setae: spear like, very large, with a single septa(notch) in center of most analyzed(biseptate).
Paraphyses: With SWOLLEN APICES.
Dehydrating all specimens folded in tissue for herbarium collection/genetic record.

results.notes: Distinctive pyramidal warts on cap surface. Found growing in oak duff within 5 feet, nearly in a ring with half a dozen or so others of the same species but different levels of maturity distinctly around the base of a large, mature live oak tree. Species apparently originally identified with pine, but more recently known to associate with oak as well. Did not find this species at this time around any other trees in the area despite wide looking at this time (looking for other Amanitas). Chose youngest, nearly pure-white specimen, but others like one pictured had various levels of browning on cap, starting with wart tips, like the top of a lemon meringue pie…
